LXIX. Mago gives like instructions about the rush also that. they call mai-iseum for weaving mats he recommends that it too be gathered in ,June and up to the middle ofJuly, giving the same instructions for drying it which Ι have mentioned in their proper place when dealing with sedge.‘¹ He distinguishes another kind of rush, which Ι find is called the marine rush and by the Greeks oxyschoenos. There are three kinds of it: the pointed, barren rusb, which the Greeks call the male, or oxys, while the other two are female, and bear a black seed. One of these, called by the Greeks melancranis, is thicker and more bushy than the first3 the third, called holoschoenus, being even more so. Of these melan- cranis is found apart from other kinds of rush, but oxys and holoschoenus grow on the same turf. The most useful for wicker-work is holoschoenus, because it is pliant and fleshy; it bears a fruit like eggs sticking to one another. The rush we have called male is sels-reproduced, the head being bent down into the earth, but melancranis is reproduced from its seed. Except for this, the roots of every kind of rush die every year.
